,"after 1323":"after 1323","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, England","England":"England","Longslow, Shropshire, England":"Onslow, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Longland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from any of the many minor places in England called Longland(s) or Langland(s). There has probably been some confusion with the Scottish surname   Langlands  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Langland","meanings":["English: topographic name from Old English <i>lang</i>, <i>long</i> ‘long’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’, ‘territory’.","Scottish: habitational name from Langlands in Guthrie (Angus).","Norwegian: variant of   Langeland  ."]},{"name":"Langlands","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Langlands in Guthrie (Angus)."]},{"name":"Longlands","meanings":["English, Scottish: variant of   Longland   with plural or post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>. There has probably been some confusion with the Scottish surname   Langlands  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":41,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":54,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Hugh Longland was born in 1274, in England as the son of Hugh Longslow. He married Alice FitzWarin about 1300. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1330, in his hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1274–1330":"1274–1330","–1330":"–1330","1298–1323":"1298–1323","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1254–1300":"1254–1300","before 1298":"enne 1298","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1345":"1345","1323":"1323","1300":"1300","1254":"1254","1298":"1298","after 1323":"pärast 1323","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, England","Eng